{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01TE9LuASXx87U5gtUp6AWxn","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→## Implementation Checklist\n     2→- [ ] 1. Confirm shared-library patterns and existing helper contracts are reused (`lib/x-agent-common.sh`, `setup_outdir`, `setup_lock`, `print_overall`) and no per-agent exception handling is introduced in bash-agent.\n     3→- [ ] 2. Create `skills/bash-agent/scripts/bash-agent.sh` with shared-lib sourcing, required knobs, and command dispatch structure that supports `syntax`, `lint`, `all`, `--fail-fast`, `help`, and unknown-command handling.\n     4→- [ ] 3. Implement `.sh` discovery logic with explicit behavior for `CHANGED_FILES` and recursive scan fallback, including `.git`, `node_modules`, and `vendor` exclusion.\n     5→- [ ] 4. Implement `run_syntax` step using `bash -n` across discovered files, aggregate full diagnostics to a per-step log, and print truncated output + `Fix:` hint on failure.\n     6→- [ ] 5. Implement `run_lint` step using `shellcheck --severity=${SHELLCHECK_SEVERITY}` across discovered files, aggregate logs, and produce shellcheck wiki link(s) in `Fix:` on failure.\n     7→- [ ] 6. Ensure command path supports `SHELLCHECK_SEVERITY` override and default severity semantics while keeping required `MAX_LINES`/`KEEP_DIR`/`FAIL_FAST` behavior intact.\n     8→- [ ] 7. Create `skills/bash-agent/SKILL.md` with trigger language and `allowed-tools` entries for RUN knobs, `SHELLCHECK_SEVERITY`, `CHANGED_FILES`, and shared controls.\n     9→- [ ] 8. Add scenario fixtures under `tests/bash-agent/clean` and `tests/bash-agent/issues`, including `scenario.env` and fixture scripts.\n    10→- [ ] 9. Validate fixture behavior: `clean` exits 0 with `shellcheck`+`bash` available, and `issues` exits 1 for intentional lint violation and/or shell syntax issue.\n    11→- [ ] 10. Update `install.sh` to include `bash-agent` in `SKILLS`, add optional dependency check messaging for `shellcheck`, and add `bash-agent` line to `print_agents_md_snippet`.\n    12→- [ ] 11. Update `README.md` with bash-agent row in Available Agents and usage examples showing `syntax`, `lint`, and `all`.\n    13→- [ ] 12. Run `shellcheck --severity=warning skills/bash-agent/scripts/bash-agent.sh` and `tests/run-scenarios.sh bash-agent` locally in validation slice, then fix and rerun until green.\n    14→- [ ] 13. Update `.ralph/exploration.md` if any implementation changed documented files, patterns, or schema.\n    15→- [ ] 14. All acceptance criteria pass — run `ralph validate work` and confirm PASS.\n    16→\n    17→## Architecture Review\n    18→\n    19→### Overall design and boundaries\n    20→The implementation is a single new command-line agent bounded to `skills/bash-agent/scripts/bash-agent.sh`, metadata in `skills/bash-agent/SKILL.md`, scenario fixtures in `tests/bash-agent`, installer wiring in `install.sh`, and user documentation in `README.md`. The data flow is deterministic and linear:\n    21→- CLI/env parsing.\n    22→- Output directory + lock setup.\n    23→- File discovery.\n    24→- Step execution (`syntax`, `lint`, or `all`).\n    25→- Step logging + result formatting.\n    26→- Final `Overall` summary and exit code.\n    27→\n    28→### Dependency graph and coupling\n    29→- Runtime dependencies for execution: `bash`, `shellcheck` (required), plus `find`, `grep`, `head`, `sort`, `uniq` from POSIX shell environment.\n    30→- Shared coupling: all common behavior comes from `lib/x-agent-common.sh` through path-based source import, so updates there affect all agents.\n    31→- Repo coupling: this spec touches five files and one optional metadata file, and is discovered automatically by `tests/run-scenarios.sh` by virtue of `tests/<agent>/scenario.env`.\n    32→- Installer coupling: adding `bash-agent` to `SKILLS` and `check_optional_deps` controls install-time messaging only; runtime behavior is independent once installed.\n    33→\n    34→### Data flow and bottlenecks\n    35→- Input: user env + command + working directory.\n    36→- Transform: discovery list -> per-step command execution -> log file output -> parsed status/fix hints.\n    37→- Output: console summary + files under `$OUTDIR`.\n    38→- Bottleneck: scanning filesystem for `.sh` files recursively when `CHANGED_FILES` is empty; mitigated with excludes and short-circuit on empty discovery.\n    39→\n    40→### Scaling characteristics and single points of failure\n    41→- Scaling is mostly linear in number of script files and shellcheck complexity.\n    42→- Single failure points are external tool execution (`bash`, `shellcheck`), lock contention, and directory traversal in large repos.\n    43→- Lock contention is serialized intentionally and can create queued latency but prevents state corruption.\n    44→\n    45→### Security architecture\n    46→- Command execution is limited to the local project files and fixed tool binaries.\n    47→- Security risks are low relative to domain; primary risks are log path tampering and shell metacharacter issues in paths.\n    48→- Mitigations:\n    49→  - Quote expanded file names in tool invocations.\n    50→  - Filter `CHANGED_FILES` to file paths and existence checks.\n    51→  - Keep lock and temp-dir usage unchanged from shared library pattern.\n    52→\n    53→## Architecture options (with tradeoffs)\n    54→\n    55→### Decision A: shared-lib-first implementation\n    56→- Option 1: Keep all boilerplate local as in older agents.\n    57→  - Effort: low.\n    58→  - Risk: high long-term drift from shared style.\n    59→  - Impact: inconsistent behavior and larger per-agent scripts.\n    60→- Option 2: Use `x-agent-common.sh` helpers (`setup_outdir`, `setup_lock`, etc.) for all shared concerns and only implement domain logic.\n    61→  - Effort: moderate implementation effort, low maintenance.\n    62→  - Risk: stronger dependency on helper interface.\n    63→  - Impact: matches existing architecture and all future agents.\n    64→- Option 3: Wrap bash-agent in a wrapper script around a generic shellcheck checker utility.\n    65→  - Effort: medium+ (new infra).\n    66→  - Risk: abstraction overhead and extra indirection.\n    67→  - Impact: future extensibility but unnecessary complexity.\n    68→- Recommended: Option 2 for consistency and minimal future maintenance.\n    69→\n    70→### Decision B: lint code extraction and fix-hint strategy\n    71→- Option 1: Static one-code hint only (first `SC####`).\n    72→  - Effort: very low.\n    73→  - Risk: under-informs when multiple shellcheck violations exist.\n    74→  - Impact: faster implementation, weaker fix signal.\n    75→- Option 2: Aggregate all unique `SC####` codes and append one wiki link per code.\n    76→  - Effort: moderate.\n    77→  - Risk: long `Fix:` line in noisy files.\n    78→  - Impact: highest signal for developers.\n    79→- Option 3: Print only tool output and no wiki links.\n    80→  - Effort: low.\n    81→  - Risk: violates FR-13 acceptance requirement.\n    82→  - Impact: insufficient for this spec.\n    83→- Recommended: Option 2, with link truncation to first 5 unique codes if necessary.\n    84→\n    85→### Decision C: behavior when `CHANGED_FILES` resolves to zero files\n    86→- Option 1: Treat as PASS.\n    87→  - Effort: minimal.\n    88→  - Risk: may mask mis-scoped inputs.\n    89→- Option 2: Treat as SKIP with explicit reason.\n    90→  - Effort: low.\n    91→  - Risk: requires test expectations for SKIP path.\n    92→  - Impact: clear caller feedback and safer with CI automation.\n    93→- Option 3: Treat as FAIL.\n    94→  - Effort: low.\n    95→  - Risk: disruptive when hook calls intentionally scope empty sets.\n    96→  - Impact: highest risk for orchestration.\n    97→- Recommended: Option 2 (`Result: SKIP (no matching .sh files)`) to make state explicit without failing workflows.\n    98→\n    99→## Code Quality Planning\n   100→\n   101→- Keep script domain size small and readable by centralizing shared behavior in `x-agent-common.sh`.\n   102→- Use small helper functions: `collect_sh_files`, `run_syntax`, `run_lint`, and `extract_shellcheck_codes`.\n   103→- Follow existing naming style: `run_<step>()` and `usage()`.\n   104→- Preserve structured output contract exactly: `Step`, `Result`, optional `Fix`, `Output`, `Full log`, `Time`, `Overall`, and `Logs` from trap.\n   105→- Use one source-of-truth list (`sh_files`) to avoid duplicated file-selection logic across syntax and lint.\n   106→- Keep helper interactions explicit; avoid nested and hidden defaults.\n   107→- Avoid clever tricks; prefer straightforward loops and explicit status flags.\n   108→- Add comment lines near `CHANGED_FILES` and `SHELLCHECK_SEVERITY` for maintainability and future agents.\n   109→\n   110→### Edge-case handling requirements\n   111→- CHANGED_FILES set and empty: validate each token is an existing `.sh` file.\n   112→- CHANGED_FILES contains missing files: ignore with warning summary count mismatch.\n   113→- Working directory has zero `.sh`: emit `SKIP` and exit 0.\n   114→- Syntax command returns non-zero on one file: continue scanning all files to collect all syntax failures in one pass.\n   115→- shellcheck output may include duplicate codes: deduplicate before composing Fix links.\n   116→- `SHELLCHECK_SEVERITY=error` should downgrade warnings and still run severity-specific checks.\n   117→- Unknown command and `-h|--help|help` should be handled before `need` checks that would block usage in non-project contexts.\n   118→\n   119→## Test Strategy\n   120→\n   121→### Coverage plan\n   122→- Unit-level command tests via direct invocation of `bash-agent` in fixture directories.\n   123→- Integration-level scenario tests through `tests/run-scenarios.sh bash-agent`.\n   124→- Static quality checks via shellcheck on the new script.\n   125→- Manual behavior validation in mixed shell-script repo to verify CHANGED_FILES scoping.\n   126→\n   127→### Explicit test coverage matrix\n   128→- `help` command: prints usage and exits 0.\n   129→- `syntax` with clean fixtures: returns PASS and no `Fix:`.\n   130→- `syntax` with intentional syntax failure: returns FAIL, full log path present, `Fix:` includes re-run guidance.\n   131→- `lint` with clean scripts: returns PASS.\n   132→- `lint` with SC2086 fixture: returns FAIL, `Fix:` includes `https://www.shellcheck.net/wiki/SC2086`.\n   133→- `all` command: runs syntax then lint with `RUN_*` gating and `FAIL_FAST` support.\n   134→- `RUN_LINT=0` and `RUN_SYNTAX=0`: skip corresponding steps.\n   135→- `CHANGED_FILES` scoping: includes only matching `.sh` and excludes directories and non-`.sh` entries.\n   136→- `SHELLCHECK_SEVERITY=error`: ignore warning-only issues in fixture; pass/fail semantics follow chosen severity.\n   137→\n   138→### Failure modes and error paths to verify\n   139→- Missing required dependency (`bash` or `shellcheck`) exits 2 with `Missing required tool: <tool>`.\n   140→- No scripts discovered after scan: `SKIP` and exit 0.\n   141→- lock already held: user sees wait message and command proceeds when lock is released.\n   142→- Scenario marked EXPECT_EXIT=1: exit 1 when syntax/lint fails.\n   143→\n   144→### Test quality assertions\n   145→- Assertions should include both command exit codes and output semantics (`Result: PASS/FAIL/SKIP`, `Fix:`, `Logs:` path).\n   146→- For lint failures, assert wiki link format exactly `https://www.shellcheck.net/wiki/SC####`.\n   147→- Keep assertions deterministic by controlling `MAX_LINES` in tests when comparing output.\n   148→\n   149→## Performance Considerations\n   150→\n   151→- `find` is O(number of files); prune known directories to prevent scanning dependency trees.\n   152→- `bash -n` and `shellcheck` are per-file/external-process heavy; avoid unnecessary extra loops.\n   153→- Use one discovery pass so both steps share the list.\n   154→- Use log files for full output to avoid large in-memory buffers.\n   155→- Memory usage remains bounded because only shell command lines and small arrays are held in process memory.\n   156→- N+1 command patterns are avoided: shellcheck is invoked once with file arguments instead of per-file calls.\n   157→\n   158→## Decision Log\n   159→\n   160→### Decision: Use shared-library helpers for output, lock, and temp lifecycle\n   161→Decision: Use `lib/x-agent-common.sh` in bash-agent and avoid reimplementing boilerplate.\n   162→Options considered:\n   163→- Keep local boilerplate in bash-agent only.\n   164→- Shared-lib-first agent implementation.\n   165→- Generic wrapper around shellcheck library.\n   166→Chosen approach: Shared-lib-first.\n   167→Implications: Lower maintenance, consistent lock/log behavior, and alignment with existing `cargo-agent`, `npm-agent`, and `terra-agent`.\n   168→\n   169→### Decision: Use one aggregated syntax pass vs early-return-on-first-error\n   170→Decision: Continue checking all discovered files and aggregate syntax failures.\n   171→Options considered:\n   172→- Exit immediately on first syntax failure.\n   173→- Aggregate all syntax failures before returning.\n   174→- Delegate to `bash -n` with file list.\n   175→Chosen approach: Aggregate.\n   176→Implications: Better developer visibility; output is more useful, slight runtime increase for bad checkouts.\n   177→\n   178→### Decision: Include one or many shellcheck wiki links in fix hint\n   179→Decision: Include one or multiple links based on discovered unique error codes.\n   180→Options considered:\n   181→- No links.\n   182→- One best-effort link.\n   183→- One link per unique code with dedupe.\n   184→Chosen approach: One link per unique code.\n   185→Implications: richer remediation guidance, longer fix line in noisy lint sessions.\n   186→\n   187→### Decision: Scoping behavior when CHANGED_FILES is empty after filtering\n   188→Decision: Skip step with explicit message.\n   189→Options considered:\n   190→- Treat as PASS.\n   191→- Treat as SKIP.\n   192→- Treat as FAIL.\n   193→Chosen approach: SKIP.\n   194→Implications: avoids false failure when user or caller passes empty scope but preserves meaningful feedback.\n   195→\n   196→## Edge Cases and Risks\n   197→\n   198→- `CHANGED_FILES` includes files with spaces in names: current split-based parsing is brittle; caller convention assumes space-separated file paths.\n   199→- `.sh` files outside repo root returned by CHANGED_FILES: filter to `-f` avoids attempting missing paths.\n   200→- Very large repositories with many `.sh` files: scan can be expensive; prune list should stay curated.\n   201→- External tool missing in minimal environments: hard dependency check must fail fast.\n   202→- `SHELLCHECK_SEVERITY` unknown: shellcheck should fail; script should surface command failure cleanly.\n   203→- Scenarios with only syntax errors and no shellcheck violations still need deterministic fail reason and logs.\n   204→- Windows line endings in fixtures: avoid regex assumptions in shellcheck code extraction that depend on Unix LF; use tolerant parsing.\n   205→\n   206→## Step-by-Step Implementation Plan\n   207→\n   208→1. What: Build a minimal `bash-agent.sh` skeleton that sources `lib/x-agent-common.sh` after `set -euo pipefail`, defines required environment toggles, and initializes output/log lifecycle.\n   209→Why: This anchors bash-agent in repository-wide helper conventions and avoids duplicated boilerplate.\n   210→How: Add script header, `SCRIPT_DIR`, `LIB_DIR`, shared source line, `RUN_SYNTAX`, `RUN_LINT`, `SHELLCHECK_SEVERITY`, and call `setup_outdir \"bash-agent\"` + `setup_lock \"bash-agent\"` near startup.\n   211→Edge Cases: Help path should work before project checks; unknown command should print usage and exit 2.\n   212→Tests: Manual `bash-agent --help` and `bash-agent syntax` in `tests/bash-agent/clean`.\n   213→Risks: Accidentally using local `OUTDIR` setup instead of `setup_outdir`.\n   214→\n   215→2. What: Implement file discovery function that produces a shared `sh_files` list used by both steps.\n   216→Why: Removes duplication and guarantees syntax/lint execute on the same target set.\n   217→How: Use `CHANGED_FILES` branch first (filter existing `*.sh`), else recursive `find` with `-prune` for `.git`, `node_modules`, and `vendor`; print `Discovered N .sh file(s)`.\n   218→Edge Cases: Nonexistent CHANGED_FILES entries, directories, hidden directories, no files found.\n   219→Tests: Synthetic calls with explicit CHANGED_FILES plus no-CHANGED_FILES directory scan.\n   220→Risks: Incorrect prune ordering could accidentally skip valid files.\n   221→\n   222→3. What: Implement `run_syntax` step.\n   223→Why: Implements FR-6 and FR-3 `syntax` capability.\n   224→How: Iterate over collected files; for each call `bash -n` and append output to `${OUTDIR}/syntax.log`; track first/aggregate failures; print truncated `Output` and `Fix: resolve syntax errors above, then re-run: /bash-agent syntax` on failure, then `print_result`.\n   225→Edge Cases: Files with permissions denied; transient parse errors; zero files discovered.\n   226→Tests: `tests/bash-agent/issues` with a script containing a syntax error and `tests/bash-agent/clean` valid script.\n   227→Risks: Short-circuiting on first file misses additional syntax failures.\n   228→\n   229→4. What: Implement `run_lint` step with shellcheck severity override.\n   230→Why: Implements FR-6 and FR-13 acceptance around shellcheck output and links.\n   231→How: Run one `shellcheck --severity=${SHELLCHECK_SEVERITY}` call with all discovered files; write to `${OUTDIR}/lint.log`; on failure parse unique codes via regex; construct `Fix` message with wiki links for each code and re-run command suggestion.\n   232→Edge Cases: `SHELLCHECK_SEVERITY=error` with warning-only issues; duplicate codes; very long error lists.\n   233→Tests: Issue fixture intentionally causing SC2086 and assertion for link presence.\n   234→Risks: Regex parsing could over-collect false positives from file content.\n   235→\n   236→5. What: Implement `main` command dispatch with `--fail-fast`, `RUN_*` toggles, and robust defaults.\n   237→Why: FR-5 and FR-4 require predictable orchestration and skip semantics.\n   238→How: Parse `--fail-fast`; command default to `all`; route `syntax`, `lint`, `all`, and help aliases; apply `should_continue` in `all` path.\n   239→Edge Cases: Empty args, command aliases, mixed uppercase/lowercase command attempts.\n   240→Tests: Direct invocation matrix: `all`, `syntax`, `lint`, `--fail-fast syntax`, `RUN_LINT=0 bash-agent all`.\n   241→Risks: Incorrect variable scoping for `overall_ok` from step failures.\n   242→\n   243→6. What: Add `skills/bash-agent/SKILL.md` with trigger language and allowed tools.\n   244→Why: Required by FR-11 and for agent orchestration compatibility.\n   245→How: Clone style from `skills/npm-agent/SKILL.md`; include `SHELLCHECK_SEVERITY=*`, `RUN_*`, and standard shared knobs.\n   246→Edge Cases: Keep script path examples consistent with others (`scripts/bash-agent.sh*`).\n   247→Tests: Manual inspection and a quick grep check that allowed patterns include `SHELLCHECK_SEVERITY=`.\n   248→Risks: Mismatched trigger language can reduce downstream routing accuracy.\n   249→\n   250→7. What: Add scenario fixtures for `clean` and `issues`.\n   251→Why: Required by FR-13 and overall acceptance.\n   252→How: Create `tests/bash-agent/clean/scenario.env` and `tests/bash-agent/issues/scenario.env`; add valid `scripts/good.sh` and intentionally lint-broken `scripts/bad.sh`.\n   253→Edge Cases: Ensure fixture paths use `scripts/` folder under scenario and keep fixture complexity minimal.\n   254→Tests: `tests/run-scenarios.sh bash-agent`.\n   255→Risks: Fixture scripts accidentally include hidden syntax errors in clean case.\n   256→\n   257→8. What: Update `install.sh` with `bash-agent` in `SKILLS`, dependency checks, and agent snippet.\n   258→Why: Required by FR-12 and expected by packaging flow.\n   259→How: Add `bash-agent` to default list, add `check_optional_deps` branch for `shellcheck`, add `bash-agent)` branch in `print_agents_md_snippet`.\n   260→Edge Cases: Optional check output should remain aligned with install style and not block installation.\n   261→Tests: `sh install.sh --help` to ensure no syntax issues and branch path review via source inspection.\n   262→Risks: Missing branch can drop bash-agent from install output and snippet recommendations.\n   263→\n   264→9. What: Update `README.md` to expose bash-agent availability.\n   265→Why: Required by FR-12 completion and discoverability.\n   266→How: Add table row and usage block with examples for `syntax`, `lint`, and `all`.\n   267→Edge Cases: Keep markdown table alignment and avoid breaking existing links/ordering.\n   268→Tests: Quick readability verification in diff review.\n   269→Risks: Skipping usage examples can create discoverability gap.\n   270→\n   271→10. What: Run quality gates for only this implementation scope.\n   272→Why: Ensures FR-13 and shell correctness before handoff.\n   273→How: Execute `shellcheck --severity=warning skills/bash-agent/scripts/bash-agent.sh` and `tests/run-scenarios.sh bash-agent`.\n   274→Edge Cases: Scenarios skipped due missing local shellcheck or shell; validate output includes skip reasons.\n   275→Tests: Gate command outputs and PASS/FAIL states.\n   276→Risks: Tool availability mismatch on contributor machines causes false-negative local runs.\n   277→\n   278→11. What: Update `.ralph/exploration.md` with newly mapped files and workflow touchpoints.\n   279→Why: Required for future specs and onboarding continuity.\n   280→How: Add bash-agent-related key files and scenario layout notes; mention new fixture path conventions.\n   281→Edge Cases: Keep file concise; do not over-document implementation details.\n   282→Tests: Visual review that sections remain machine-readable and up to date.\n   283→Risks: Drift if outdated architecture notes are preserved.\n   284→\n   285→12. What: Final gate validation.\n   286→Why: Required by protocol before completion.\n   287→How: Execute `ralph validate work` and require PASS in logs.\n   288→Edge Cases: If validation fails, fix plan artifact only and rerun.\n   289→Tests: `ralph validate work`.\n   290→Risks: Validation format mismatch from checklist structure.\n   291→\n   292→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c026452d-4e68-40df-a262-fb1f2cd29fde","uuid":"03e3d15c-eaeb-4179-85b1-f0daeb073c1f","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/chrisraethke/projects/x-agent/.ralph/work-plan.txt","content":"## Implementation Checklist\n- [ ] 1. Confirm shared-library patterns and existing helper contracts are reused (`lib/x-agent-common.sh`, `setup_outdir`, `setup_lock`, `print_overall`) and no per-agent exception handling is introduced in bash-agent.\n- [ ] 2. Create `skills/bash-agent/scripts/bash-agent.sh` with shared-lib sourcing, required knobs, and command dispatch structure that supports `syntax`, `lint`, `all`, `--fail-fast`, `help`, and unknown-command handling.\n- [ ] 3. Implement `.sh` discovery logic with explicit behavior for `CHANGED_FILES` and recursive scan fallback, including `.git`, `node_modules`, and `vendor` exclusion.\n- [ ] 4. Implement `run_syntax` step using `bash -n` across discovered files, aggregate full diagnostics to a per-step log, and print truncated output + `Fix:` hint on failure.\n- [ ] 5. Implement `run_lint` step using `shellcheck --severity=${SHELLCHECK_SEVERITY}` across discovered files, aggregate logs, and produce shellcheck wiki link(s) in `Fix:` on failure.\n- [ ] 6. Ensure command path supports `SHELLCHECK_SEVERITY` override and default severity semantics while keeping required `MAX_LINES`/`KEEP_DIR`/`FAIL_FAST` behavior intact.\n- [ ] 7. Create `skills/bash-agent/SKILL.md` with trigger language and `allowed-tools` entries for RUN knobs, `SHELLCHECK_SEVERITY`, `CHANGED_FILES`, and shared controls.\n- [ ] 8. Add scenario fixtures under `tests/bash-agent/clean` and `tests/bash-agent/issues`, including `scenario.env` and fixture scripts.\n- [ ] 9. Validate fixture behavior: `clean` exits 0 with `shellcheck`+`bash` available, and `issues` exits 1 for intentional lint violation and/or shell syntax issue.\n- [ ] 10. Update `install.sh` to include `bash-agent` in `SKILLS`, add optional dependency check messaging for `shellcheck`, and add `bash-agent` line to `print_agents_md_snippet`.\n- [ ] 11. Update `README.md` with bash-agent row in Available Agents and usage examples showing `syntax`, `lint`, and `all`.\n- [ ] 12. Run `shellcheck --severity=warning skills/bash-agent/scripts/bash-agent.sh` and `tests/run-scenarios.sh bash-agent` locally in validation slice, then fix and rerun until green.\n- [ ] 13. Update `.ralph/exploration.md` if any implementation changed documented files, patterns, or schema.\n- [ ] 14. All acceptance criteria pass — run `ralph validate work` and confirm PASS.\n\n## Architecture Review\n\n### Overall design and boundaries\nThe implementation is a single new command-line agent bounded to `skills/bash-agent/scripts/bash-agent.sh`, metadata in `skills/bash-agent/SKILL.md`, scenario fixtures in `tests/bash-agent`, installer wiring in `install.sh`, and user documentation in `README.md`. The data flow is deterministic and linear:\n- CLI/env parsing.\n- Output directory + lock setup.\n- File discovery.\n- Step execution (`syntax`, `lint`, or `all`).\n- Step logging + result formatting.\n- Final `Overall` summary and exit code.\n\n### Dependency graph and coupling\n- Runtime dependencies for execution: `bash`, `shellcheck` (required), plus `find`, `grep`, `head`, `sort`, `uniq` from POSIX shell environment.\n- Shared coupling: all common behavior comes from `lib/x-agent-common.sh` through path-based source import, so updates there affect all agents.\n- Repo coupling: this spec touches five files and one optional metadata file, and is discovered automatically by `tests/run-scenarios.sh` by virtue of `tests/<agent>/scenario.env`.\n- Installer coupling: adding `bash-agent` to `SKILLS` and `check_optional_deps` controls install-time messaging only; runtime behavior is independent once installed.\n\n### Data flow and bottlenecks\n- Input: user env + command + working directory.\n- Transform: discovery list -> per-step command execution -> log file output -> parsed status/fix hints.\n- Output: console summary + files under `$OUTDIR`.\n- Bottleneck: scanning filesystem for `.sh` files recursively when `CHANGED_FILES` is empty; mitigated with excludes and short-circuit on empty discovery.\n\n### Scaling characteristics and single points of failure\n- Scaling is mostly linear in number of script files and shellcheck complexity.\n- Single failure points are external tool execution (`bash`, `shellcheck`), lock contention, and directory traversal in large repos.\n- Lock contention is serialized intentionally and can create queued latency but prevents state corruption.\n\n### Security architecture\n- Command execution is limited to the local project files and fixed tool binaries.\n- Security risks are low relative to domain; primary risks are log path tampering and shell metacharacter issues in paths.\n- Mitigations:\n  - Quote expanded file names in tool invocations.\n  - Filter `CHANGED_FILES` to file paths and existence checks.\n  - Keep lock and temp-dir usage unchanged from shared library pattern.\n\n## Architecture options (with tradeoffs)\n\n### Decision A: shared-lib-first implementation\n- Option 1: Keep all boilerplate local as in older agents.\n  - Effort: low.\n  - Risk: high long-term drift from shared style.\n  - Impact: inconsistent behavior and larger per-agent scripts.\n- Option 2: Use `x-agent-common.sh` helpers (`setup_outdir`, `setup_lock`, etc.) for all shared concerns and only implement domain logic.\n  - Effort: moderate implementation effort, low maintenance.\n  - Risk: stronger dependency on helper interface.\n  - Impact: matches existing architecture and all future agents.\n- Option 3: Wrap bash-agent in a wrapper script around a generic shellcheck checker utility.\n  - Effort: medium+ (new infra).\n  - Risk: abstraction overhead and extra indirection.\n  - Impact: future extensibility but unnecessary complexity.\n- Recommended: Option 2 for consistency and minimal future maintenance.\n\n### Decision B: lint code extraction and fix-hint strategy\n- Option 1: Static one-code hint only (first `SC####`).\n  - Effort: very low.\n  - Risk: under-informs when multiple shellcheck violations exist.\n  - Impact: faster implementation, weaker fix signal.\n- Option 2: Aggregate all unique `SC####` codes and append one wiki link per code.\n  - Effort: moderate.\n  - Risk: long `Fix:` line in noisy files.\n  - Impact: highest signal for developers.\n- Option 3: Print only tool output and no wiki links.\n  - Effort: low.\n  - Risk: violates FR-13 acceptance requirement.\n  - Impact: insufficient for this spec.\n- Recommended: Option 2, with link truncation to first 5 unique codes if necessary.\n\n### Decision C: behavior when `CHANGED_FILES` resolves to zero files\n- Option 1: Treat as PASS.\n  - Effort: minimal.\n  - Risk: may mask mis-scoped inputs.\n- Option 2: Treat as SKIP with explicit reason.\n  - Effort: low.\n  - Risk: requires test expectations for SKIP path.\n  - Impact: clear caller feedback and safer with CI automation.\n- Option 3: Treat as FAIL.\n  - Effort: low.\n  - Risk: disruptive when hook calls intentionally scope empty sets.\n  - Impact: highest risk for orchestration.\n- Recommended: Option 2 (`Result: SKIP (no matching .sh files)`) to make state explicit without failing workflows.\n\n## Code Quality Planning\n\n- Keep script domain size small and readable by centralizing shared behavior in `x-agent-common.sh`.\n- Use small helper functions: `collect_sh_files`, `run_syntax`, `run_lint`, and `extract_shellcheck_codes`.\n- Follow existing naming style: `run_<step>()` and `usage()`.\n- Preserve structured output contract exactly: `Step`, `Result`, optional `Fix`, `Output`, `Full log`, `Time`, `Overall`, and `Logs` from trap.\n- Use one source-of-truth list (`sh_files`) to avoid duplicated file-selection logic across syntax and lint.\n- Keep helper interactions explicit; avoid nested and hidden defaults.\n- Avoid clever tricks; prefer straightforward loops and explicit status flags.\n- Add comment lines near `CHANGED_FILES` and `SHELLCHECK_SEVERITY` for maintainability and future agents.\n\n### Edge-case handling requirements\n- CHANGED_FILES set and empty: validate each token is an existing `.sh` file.\n- CHANGED_FILES contains missing files: ignore with warning summary count mismatch.\n- Working directory has zero `.sh`: emit `SKIP` and exit 0.\n- Syntax command returns non-zero on one file: continue scanning all files to collect all syntax failures in one pass.\n- shellcheck output may include duplicate codes: deduplicate before composing Fix links.\n- `SHELLCHECK_SEVERITY=error` should downgrade warnings and still run severity-specific checks.\n- Unknown command and `-h|--help|help` should be handled before `need` checks that would block usage in non-project contexts.\n\n## Test Strategy\n\n### Coverage plan\n- Unit-level command tests via direct invocation of `bash-agent` in fixture directories.\n- Integration-level scenario tests through `tests/run-scenarios.sh bash-agent`.\n- Static quality checks via shellcheck on the new script.\n- Manual behavior validation in mixed shell-script repo to verify CHANGED_FILES scoping.\n\n### Explicit test coverage matrix\n- `help` command: prints usage and exits 0.\n- `syntax` with clean fixtures: returns PASS and no `Fix:`.\n- `syntax` with intentional syntax failure: returns FAIL, full log path present, `Fix:` includes re-run guidance.\n- `lint` with clean scripts: returns PASS.\n- `lint` with SC2086 fixture: returns FAIL, `Fix:` includes `https://www.shellcheck.net/wiki/SC2086`.\n- `all` command: runs syntax then lint with `RUN_*` gating and `FAIL_FAST` support.\n- `RUN_LINT=0` and `RUN_SYNTAX=0`: skip corresponding steps.\n- `CHANGED_FILES` scoping: includes only matching `.sh` and excludes directories and non-`.sh` entries.\n- `SHELLCHECK_SEVERITY=error`: ignore warning-only issues in fixture; pass/fail semantics follow chosen severity.\n\n### Failure modes and error paths to verify\n- Missing required dependency (`bash` or `shellcheck`) exits 2 with `Missing required tool: <tool>`.\n- No scripts discovered after scan: `SKIP` and exit 0.\n- lock already held: user sees wait message and command proceeds when lock is released.\n- Scenario marked EXPECT_EXIT=1: exit 1 when syntax/lint fails.\n\n### Test quality assertions\n- Assertions should include both command exit codes and output semantics (`Result: PASS/FAIL/SKIP`, `Fix:`, `Logs:` path).\n- For lint failures, assert wiki link format exactly `https://www.shellcheck.net/wiki/SC####`.\n- Keep assertions deterministic by controlling `MAX_LINES` in tests when comparing output.\n\n## Performance Considerations\n\n- `find` is O(number of files); prune known directories to prevent scanning dependency trees.\n- `bash -n` and `shellcheck` are per-file/external-process heavy; avoid unnecessary extra loops.\n- Use one discovery pass so both steps share the list.\n- Use log files for full output to avoid large in-memory buffers.\n- Memory usage remains bounded because only shell command lines and small arrays are held in process memory.\n- N+1 command patterns are avoided: shellcheck is invoked once with file arguments instead of per-file calls.\n\n## Decision Log\n\n### Decision: Use shared-library helpers for output, lock, and temp lifecycle\nDecision: Use `lib/x-agent-common.sh` in bash-agent and avoid reimplementing boilerplate.\nOptions considered:\n- Keep local boilerplate in bash-agent only.\n- Shared-lib-first agent implementation.\n- Generic wrapper around shellcheck library.\nChosen approach: Shared-lib-first.\nImplications: Lower maintenance, consistent lock/log behavior, and alignment with existing `cargo-agent`, `npm-agent`, and `terra-agent`.\n\n### Decision: Use one aggregated syntax pass vs early-return-on-first-error\nDecision: Continue checking all discovered files and aggregate syntax failures.\nOptions considered:\n- Exit immediately on first syntax failure.\n- Aggregate all syntax failures before returning.\n- Delegate to `bash -n` with file list.\nChosen approach: Aggregate.\nImplications: Better developer visibility; output is more useful, slight runtime increase for bad checkouts.\n\n### Decision: Include one or many shellcheck wiki links in fix hint\nDecision: Include one or multiple links based on discovered unique error codes.\nOptions considered:\n- No links.\n- One best-effort link.\n- One link per unique code with dedupe.\nChosen approach: One link per unique code.\nImplications: richer remediation guidance, longer fix line in noisy lint sessions.\n\n### Decision: Scoping behavior when CHANGED_FILES is empty after filtering\nDecision: Skip step with explicit message.\nOptions considered:\n- Treat as PASS.\n- Treat as SKIP.\n- Treat as FAIL.\nChosen approach: SKIP.\nImplications: avoids false failure when user or caller passes empty scope but preserves meaningful feedback.\n\n## Edge Cases and Risks\n\n- `CHANGED_FILES` includes files with spaces in names: current split-based parsing is brittle; caller convention assumes space-separated file paths.\n- `.sh` files outside repo root returned by CHANGED_FILES: filter to `-f` avoids attempting missing paths.\n- Very large repositories with many `.sh` files: scan can be expensive; prune list should stay curated.\n- External tool missing in minimal environments: hard dependency check must fail fast.\n- `SHELLCHECK_SEVERITY` unknown: shellcheck should fail; script should surface command failure cleanly.\n- Scenarios with only syntax errors and no shellcheck violations still need deterministic fail reason and logs.\n- Windows line endings in fixtures: avoid regex assumptions in shellcheck code extraction that depend on Unix LF; use tolerant parsing.\n\n## Step-by-Step Implementation Plan\n\n1. What: Build a minimal `bash-agent.sh` skeleton that sources `lib/x-agent-common.sh` after `set -euo pipefail`, defines required environment toggles, and initializes output/log lifecycle.\nWhy: This anchors bash-agent in repository-wide helper conventions and avoids duplicated boilerplate.\nHow: Add script header, `SCRIPT_DIR`, `LIB_DIR`, shared source line, `RUN_SYNTAX`, `RUN_LINT`, `SHELLCHECK_SEVERITY`, and call `setup_outdir \"bash-agent\"` + `setup_lock \"bash-agent\"` near startup.\nEdge Cases: Help path should work before project checks; unknown command should print usage and exit 2.\nTests: Manual `bash-agent --help` and `bash-agent syntax` in `tests/bash-agent/clean`.\nRisks: Accidentally using local `OUTDIR` setup instead of `setup_outdir`.\n\n2. What: Implement file discovery function that produces a shared `sh_files` list used by both steps.\nWhy: Removes duplication and guarantees syntax/lint execute on the same target set.\nHow: Use `CHANGED_FILES` branch first (filter existing `*.sh`), else recursive `find` with `-prune` for `.git`, `node_modules`, and `vendor`; print `Discovered N .sh file(s)`.\nEdge Cases: Nonexistent CHANGED_FILES entries, directories, hidden directories, no files found.\nTests: Synthetic calls with explicit CHANGED_FILES plus no-CHANGED_FILES directory scan.\nRisks: Incorrect prune ordering could accidentally skip valid files.\n\n3. What: Implement `run_syntax` step.\nWhy: Implements FR-6 and FR-3 `syntax` capability.\nHow: Iterate over collected files; for each call `bash -n` and append output to `${OUTDIR}/syntax.log`; track first/aggregate failures; print truncated `Output` and `Fix: resolve syntax errors above, then re-run: /bash-agent syntax` on failure, then `print_result`.\nEdge Cases: Files with permissions denied; transient parse errors; zero files discovered.\nTests: `tests/bash-agent/issues` with a script containing a syntax error and `tests/bash-agent/clean` valid script.\nRisks: Short-circuiting on first file misses additional syntax failures.\n\n4. What: Implement `run_lint` step with shellcheck severity override.\nWhy: Implements FR-6 and FR-13 acceptance around shellcheck output and links.\nHow: Run one `shellcheck --severity=${SHELLCHECK_SEVERITY}` call with all discovered files; write to `${OUTDIR}/lint.log`; on failure parse unique codes via regex; construct `Fix` message with wiki links for each code and re-run command suggestion.\nEdge Cases: `SHELLCHECK_SEVERITY=error` with warning-only issues; duplicate codes; very long error lists.\nTests: Issue fixture intentionally causing SC2086 and assertion for link presence.\nRisks: Regex parsing could over-collect false positives from file content.\n\n5. What: Implement `main` command dispatch with `--fail-fast`, `RUN_*` toggles, and robust defaults.\nWhy: FR-5 and FR-4 require predictable orchestration and skip semantics.\nHow: Parse `--fail-fast`; command default to `all`; route `syntax`, `lint`, `all`, and help aliases; apply `should_continue` in `all` path.\nEdge Cases: Empty args, command aliases, mixed uppercase/lowercase command attempts.\nTests: Direct invocation matrix: `all`, `syntax`, `lint`, `--fail-fast syntax`, `RUN_LINT=0 bash-agent all`.\nRisks: Incorrect variable scoping for `overall_ok` from step failures.\n\n6. What: Add `skills/bash-agent/SKILL.md` with trigger language and allowed tools.\nWhy: Required by FR-11 and for agent orchestration compatibility.\nHow: Clone style from `skills/npm-agent/SKILL.md`; include `SHELLCHECK_SEVERITY=*`, `RUN_*`, and standard shared knobs.\nEdge Cases: Keep script path examples consistent with others (`scripts/bash-agent.sh*`).\nTests: Manual inspection and a quick grep check that allowed patterns include `SHELLCHECK_SEVERITY=`.\nRisks: Mismatched trigger language can reduce downstream routing accuracy.\n\n7. What: Add scenario fixtures for `clean` and `issues`.\nWhy: Required by FR-13 and overall acceptance.\nHow: Create `tests/bash-agent/clean/scenario.env` and `tests/bash-agent/issues/scenario.env`; add valid `scripts/good.sh` and intentionally lint-broken `scripts/bad.sh`.\nEdge Cases: Ensure fixture paths use `scripts/` folder under scenario and keep fixture complexity minimal.\nTests: `tests/run-scenarios.sh bash-agent`.\nRisks: Fixture scripts accidentally include hidden syntax errors in clean case.\n\n8. What: Update `install.sh` with `bash-agent` in `SKILLS`, dependency checks, and agent snippet.\nWhy: Required by FR-12 and expected by packaging flow.\nHow: Add `bash-agent` to default list, add `check_optional_deps` branch for `shellcheck`, add `bash-agent)` branch in `print_agents_md_snippet`.\nEdge Cases: Optional check output should remain aligned with install style and not block installation.\nTests: `sh install.sh --help` to ensure no syntax issues and branch path review via source inspection.\nRisks: Missing branch can drop bash-agent from install output and snippet recommendations.\n\n9. What: Update `README.md` to expose bash-agent availability.\nWhy: Required by FR-12 completion and discoverability.\nHow: Add table row and usage block with examples for `syntax`, `lint`, and `all`.\nEdge Cases: Keep markdown table alignment and avoid breaking existing links/ordering.\nTests: Quick readability verification in diff review.\nRisks: Skipping usage examples can create discoverability gap.\n\n10. What: Run quality gates for only this implementation scope.\nWhy: Ensures FR-13 and shell correctness before handoff.\nHow: Execute `shellcheck --severity=warning skills/bash-agent/scripts/bash-agent.sh` and `tests/run-scenarios.sh bash-agent`.\nEdge Cases: Scenarios skipped due missing local shellcheck or shell; validate output includes skip reasons.\nTests: Gate command outputs and PASS/FAIL states.\nRisks: Tool availability mismatch on contributor machines causes false-negative local runs.\n\n11. What: Update `.ralph/exploration.md` with newly mapped files and workflow touchpoints.\nWhy: Required for future specs and onboarding continuity.\nHow: Add bash-agent-related key files and scenario layout notes; mention new fixture path conventions.\nEdge Cases: Keep file concise; do not over-document implementation details.\nTests: Visual review that sections remain machine-readable and up to date.\nRisks: Drift if outdated architecture notes are preserved.\n\n12. What: Final gate validation.\nWhy: Required by protocol before completion.\nHow: Execute `ralph validate work` and require PASS in logs.\nEdge Cases: If validation fails, fix plan artifact only and rerun.\nTests: `ralph validate work`.\nRisks: Validation format mismatch from checklist structure.\n\n","numLines":292,"startLine":1,"totalLines":292}}}
